Ethical Considerations:

  • The Ames Housing data was collected from the years 2006 to 2010 from the City Assessors office in Ames Iowa by professor Dean de Cock from Truman State University. The procurement of this data set was primarily intended for teaching purposes with machine learning.

  • Regarding ethical concerns, the data collected by the Assessors office is information routinely collected for taxation purposes, which is readily accessible to the public. Because the data was already available to the public, all the data was obtained legally, and no process was taken to obtain permission from the property owners to use their data. It is also important to note that any and all identifying information of the properties and their owners were not used, therefore protecting the identity of the individual.

  • While there doesnt appear to be any ethical issues behind the procurement of this data, some broader thoughts on how the data can be used may have some different ethical questions. Private companies using this dataset to maximize the most profit from selling a house by including the bare minimum of what is needed for a homebuyer could start a trend where there are less items in a home that can improve the quality of life for the homebuyer if they dont have a significant contribution to the sale price of the house.

  • On the other hand, data like this can be used for good intentions. Companies can see what homebuyers value most and use that information to tailor their needs and wants with future housing projects. Furthermore, using this dataset for teaching curriculums and educational purposes is a positive way to use it.

  • Overall, ethical concerns of data can vary widely and is still a topic of great discussion with many gray areas. With data becoming such a valuable resource in our world, it is important for all researchers to consider these ethical questions and be able to make the right decisions as we pave the way in using these new technologies.

Citation:

De Cock, D. (2011). Ames, Iowa: Alternative to the Boston Housing Data as an End of Semester Regression Project. Journal of Statistics Education, 19(3). Retrieved from https://jse.amstat.org/v19n3/decock.pdf

This notebook aims to complete data wrangling of the housing dataset and see which features in utilities has the largest affect on house sale prices. the features that are considered as utilities in this study include:

Utilities (In General):

  • Utilities: Type of utilities available

AllPub - All public Utilities (E,G,W,& S)

NoSewr - Electricity, Gas, and Water (Septic Tank)

NoSeWa - Electricity and Gas Only

ELO - Electricity only

  • Heating: Type of heating

Floor - Floor Furnace

GasA - Gas forced warm air furnace

GasW - Gas hot water or steam heat

Grav - gravity furnace

OthW - Hot water or steam heat other than gas

Wall - Wall furnace

  • HeatingQC: Heating quality and condition

Ex - Excellent

Gd - Good

TA - Average/Typical

Fa - Fair

Po - Poor

  • Maybe use this CentralAir: Central air conditioning
  • Electrical: Electrical system

SBrkr - Standard Circuit Breakers & Romex

Fuse A - Fuse Box over 60 AMP and all Romex wiring (average)

Fuse F - 60 AMP Fuse Box and mostly Romex wiring (Fair)

Fuse P - 60 AMP Fuse Box and mostly knob & tube wiring (poor)

Mix - Mixed

What does our data tell us about each feature and how it relates to Saleprice of a home? Let's break it down.

Utilities: There isn't much data to compare within this feature to make any groundbreaking findings.

Heating Quality: There is no significant difference between the level of quality of Heating and Sale price of a home, but there are slight subtle differences that could suggest a pattern - better heating quality having higher sale price.

Heating Type: There isn't enough data in observations other than GasA, this may only tell us what the more common types of Heating Types are used rather than what has a higher correlation with higher home sale prices.

Electrical system: There are no significant differences between the Electrical system types used in homes, although there is a slight subtle difference in the means between SBrkr "Standard Breaker" and the other types. SBrkr has a slightly higher mean. The amount of recorded SBrkr electrical systems being higher than the other ones may suggest that it is a more widely use type.

CentrailAir: There is no significant difference between having centrail airconditioning but the data does suggest this correlation of having centrail air conditioning and having a higher sale price when comparing the two means of "Yes" and "No" repsonses.

Year Built: There appears to be a trend between the year the home was built and sale price. It seems as though the the newer the home gets, the higher the mean price of each home will cost. Still no significant difference.

Sale Condition: The data suggests that the partial observation tends to have a higher sale price than the other homes.
